{
  "doc_id": "33641",
  "text": "Despite the clinical consequences of IPFP excision being poorly understood, the IPFP is often surgically removed to improve the view of the tibial plateau when performing total knee arthroplasty [CITATION_1] . Nevertheless, the IPFP is innervated by nociceptive nerve fibers, and may be an important structural determinant of knee pain [CITATION_2] . In a retrospective observational study of people who predominantly had knee OA, IPFP resection resulted in increased knee pain [CITATION_3] . Similarly, in a randomized controlled trial of IPFP resection or preservation at total knee arthroplasty for rheumatoid arthritis, increased anterior knee pain was noted after IPFP resection [CITATION_4] . These data support the concept that the preservation of the IPFP may help to attenuate knee pain.",
  "correct_citation": {
